<p><a href="https://openstax.org/details/books/chemistry-2e">OpenStax Chemistry 2e</a></p>
</li>
</ol></div><div><h2>Introduction to Symbolic Calculus in Python</h2><p>The purpose of this lesson is to help students develop skills in performing symbolic calculus manipulations of scalar functions of single or multiple variables using SymPy.</p><h2>Lesson Learning Outcomes (LOs)</h2><p>At the end of this lesson, students will be able to...</p><h3>Cyberinfrastructure LOs</h3><ol>
<li>
<p>Evaluate limits of scalar functions of one or multiple variables</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Perform symbolic derivatives of scalar functions of one or multiple variables</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Perform indefinite integrals of scalar functions of one or multiple variables</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Evaluate definite integrals of scalar functions of one or multiple variables</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Visualize SymPy expressions graphically</p>
</li>
</ol><h2>Lesson Prerequisites</h2><h3>CI Prereqs</h3><ul>
<li>
<p><a href="../python-basics/python-syntax.ipynb">Basic Python Syntax</a></p>
</li>
<li>
<p><a href="symbolic-algebra.ipynb">Symbolic Algebra</a></p>
</li>
</ul><h3>Content Prereqs</h3><p>This lesson is focused on the development of the <em>cyberinfrastructure skills</em> for performing symbolic calculus operations on real-valued scalar functions in Python rather than teaching the calculus itself. Students are therefore expected to be able to perform by hand the following operations from single-variable calculus:</p><ul>
<li>
<p>Limits of scalar functions of a single variable</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Ordinary derivatives of scalar functions of a single variable</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Indefinite integrals of scalar functions of a single variable</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Definite integrals of scalar functions of a single varialbe</p>
</li>
</ul><p>Because this lesson is developed with a student in a science course as the intended audience, however, some brief conceptual reminders of the behavior of these operations are provided to bring students back up to speed.</p><aside class="admonition note"><p class="admonition-title">Note</p><p class="admonition-title">Note: Multivariate Calculus</p><p>No familiarity with the calculus of scalar functions of multiple variables is assumed. Instead, these concepts are introduced as natural extensions of the calculus of scalar functions of a single variable.</p></aside><h2>Resources</h2><h3>Related Lessons</h3><ul>
